To find the area of triangle $ABC$, we first need to calculate the area of the square formed by extending the line $BC$ to point $D$. The square has a side length of 16 cm (half the length of the base of the given triangle). 
Now, we can calculate the area of this square.
The area of the square can be found by squaring its side length. So, we multiply 16 cm by 16 cm.
\begin{align*}
\text{Area of square} &= 16 \text{ cm} \cdot 16 \text{ cm} \\
&= 256 \text{ square cm.}
\end{align*}
The area of triangle $ABC$ will be half the area of this square formed by extending the line $BC$ to point $D$.
To find the area of the triangle, we need to divide the area of the square by 2.
\begin{align*}
\text{Area of triangle } ABC &= \frac{1}{2} \cdot \text{ Area of square } BCDE \\
&= \frac{1}{2} \cdot 256 \text{ square cm} \\
&= \frac{256}{2} \text{ square cm} \\
&= \boxed{128} \text{ square cm.}
\end{align*}
The area of triangle $ABC$ is $\boxed{128}$ square cm.
Therefore, we have our answer.

