To compute $\begin{pmatrix} 2 & - 1 \\ - 3 & 4 \end{pmatrix} \begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ - 1 \end{pmatrix}$, we need to follow the steps of matrix multiplication.
1.  Matrix A has dimensions 2x2 and Matrix B has dimensions 2x1. To multiply these two matrices, the number of columns in Matrix A must be equal to the number of rows in Matrix B. In this case, both have the required dimensions for multiplication.
2.  We multiply each element in the rows of Matrix A by the corresponding elements in the column of Matrix B and sum the product.
For the first element in the resulting matrix, we multiply the first row of Matrix A (2, -1) by the column of Matrix B (3, -1):
(2)(3) + (-1)(-1) = 6 + 1 = 7.
So, the first element of the resulting matrix is 7.
3.  Now we multiply the second row of Matrix A (-3, 4) by the column of Matrix B (3, -1):
(-3)(3) + 4(-1) = -9 - 4 = -13.
So, the second element of the resulting matrix is -13.
So, the resulting matrix is \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -13 \end{pmatrix}}.
Therefore, the product of $\begin{pmatrix} 2 & - 1 \\ - 3 & 4 \end{pmatrix}$ and $\begin{pmatrix} 3 \\ - 1 \end{pmatrix}$ is $\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -13 \end{pmatrix}}.$
This can also be written as \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 2*3+(-1)*(-1) \\ (-3)*3+4*(-1) \end{pmatrix}}  by simplifying the multiplication in the original problem
\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} (2 * 3) + (-1 * -1) \\ (-3 * 3) + 4 * (-1) \end{pmatrix}} also simplifies down to the same \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 6 + 1 \\ -9 + (-4) \end{pmatrix}}
\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 6 + 1 \\ -9 - 4 \end{pmatrix}} also rearranges to the same \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -13 \end{pmatrix}}
\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} (2 * 3) + (-1 * -1) \\ (-3 * 3) + 4 * (-1) \end{pmatrix}} simplifies down Further to \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} (2*3) + 1^1 \\ -3*3 + (4*-1) \end{pmatrix}}
\begin{aligned} &\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 2*3+1 \\ -3*3+4*-1 \end{pmatrix}} \ \implies\ &\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} (2*3)+1^{1} \\ (-3*3)+(4*-1) \end{pmatrix}}  \ \implies\ &\boxed{\begin{pmatrix} (2*3)+1^1 \\ (-3)^1+(4*-1) \end{pmatrix}} \ \implies\ &\boxed{\begin{pmatrix}  (2*3)  +1 \\   -3+ (4*-1) \end{pmatrix}}  \\ \end{aligned}
\boxed{\begin{pmatrix}   (2 * 3) +1   \\   -3  +  (-4)  \end{pmatrix}}
\begin{aligned} &\boxed{\begin{pmatrix}  (2 * 3) +1   \\   -3  +  (-4)  \end{pmatrix}} \\ \implies \ & \boxed{\begin{pmatrix}  6 +  1 \\   (-3 + (-4)) \end{pmatrix}} \\ \implies \ & \boxed{\begin{pmatrix}  7 \\    (-7)  \end{pmatrix}} \\ \implies \ & \boxed{\begin{pmatrix}  7 \\   -7  \end{pmatrix}} \\ \end{aligned}
This final simplified version \boxed{\begin{pmatrix}  7 \\   -7 \end{pmatrix}} is the same as the original result \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -13 \end{pmatrix}}
Both original and the alternative version have same result \boxed{\begin{pmatrix} 7 \\ -13 \end{pmatrix}}
